Our main objective was to minimize the number of new cases in symptomatic classes and the costs required to control epidemic. Consequently, the objective functional was defined as

\[G\big{(}u(t)\big{)}=\int_{0}^{T}\left[\sum_{j=1}^{k}\big{(}p_{mj}l_{mj}+p_{fj} l_{fj}\big{)}+\frac{p_{k+1}}{2}u_{1}^{2}(t)+\frac{p_{k+2}}{2}u_{2}^{2}(t)+ \frac{p_{k+3}}{2}u_{3}^{2}(t)\right]dt, \tag{3}\]

where, the constants \(p_{mj},p_{fj}\), \((j=1,...,k)\) are the weight factors for the symptomatic classes \(l_{mj},l_{fj}\), \((j=1,...,k)\), respectively, while \(p_{k+1},p_{k+2}\), and \(p_{k+3}\) are the corresponding cost factors. The core task was to determine the optimal controls for \(u^{*}=(u_{1}^{*},u_{2}^{*},u_{3}^{*})\) based on the Pontryagin maximum principle, such that

\[G(u^{*})=min_{\Theta}G\big{(}u(t)\big{)}, \tag{4}\]

where, \(\Theta=\{u(t)\in L^{3}(0,T)|u_{min}\leq u_{1}(t),u_{2}(t),u_{3}(t)\leq u_{max}, t\in(0,T)\}\) is the control set, T is represented the final step size, and \(L^{3}(0,T)\) is the set of integrable functions defined on the interval \((0,T)\).

To begin solving the optimal problem, we focused on the Lagrangian and Hamiltonian for Eqs. (2) to (4). The Lagrangian for the optimal problem is defined as follows:

\[\mathcal{L}=\sum_{j=1}^{k}\big{(}p_{mj}l_{mj}+p_{fj}l_{fj}\big{)}+\frac{p_{k+1} }{2}u_{1}^{2}(t)+\frac{p_{k+2}}{2}u_{2}^{2}(t)+\frac{p_{k+3}}{2}u_{3}^{2}(t). \tag{5}\]

To find the minimum value of Eq. (5), we introduced the Hamiltonian function \(\mathcal{H}\) defined as follows:\[\mathcal{H}=L+\sum_{i=1}^{10k+5}\eta_{i}f_{i}, \tag{6}\]

